## Executive Summary

This room is foundational theory for anyone approaching Active Directory exploitation. Before attacking AD, you need to understand what you're attacking — the structure of domains, how authentication works, what BloodHound is actually mapping when it shows attack paths, and why certain accounts and groups are inherently dangerous. Active Directory is 40 points on the OSCP exam and all-or-nothing, making this conceptual groundwork critical.

The room covers AD architecture, object types, Group Policy, Kerberos authentication, and trust relationships — the building blocks that every subsequent AD attack (Kerberoasting, AS-REP Roasting, Pass-the-Hash, DCSync) depends on.

**Key concepts covered:**
- Domain architecture — objects, OUs, trees, forests
- Users, groups, and machine accounts
- Group Policy Objects (GPOs) and their attack surface
- Kerberos authentication flow (TGT/TGS)
- NTLM authentication and its weaknesses
- Domain trust relationships

**Verdict:** Required reading before touching any AD attack tooling. Understanding why attacks work makes them stick.

