## Domain Trusts

Trust relationships allow users in one domain to access resources in another.

| Trust Type | Direction | Description |
|------------|-----------|-------------|
| One-way trust | → | Domain A trusts Domain B (B can access A's resources) |
| Two-way trust | ↔ | Both domains trust each other |
| Transitive trust | A↔B, B↔C → A↔C | Trust flows through the chain |
| Forest trust | Forest-level | Explicit trust between separate forests |

**Attacker relevance:** In a multi-domain forest, compromising a child domain often leads to forest root compromise via the `SID History` attribute or the `Enterprise Admins` group. Cross-domain and cross-forest attacks are advanced OSCP territory but appear in challenge labs.

